[Encephalitis cases, with fatalities, continue to occur in north
eastern India. The above report implicates pigs and mosquitoes,
suggesting that the medical authorities believe that the etiological
agent involved in these cases is Japanese encephalitis (JE) virus,
which is likely to be correct. Laboratory confirmation is needed to
confirm the diagnosis. Pigs are amplifying hosts of JE virus. Wild
birds are the reservoir hosts and alone can serve as sources of
infectious blood meals for transmission to humans. The suggestion that
an infected human introduced the virus is incorrect for JE virus.
Human viremias are not of sufficient magnitude and duration to infect
vector mosquitoes. Thus, humans are dead end hosts. The proportion of
individuals in this area who are immunized against JE virus is not
stated in this report.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Bansihari in
Bengal state can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/17vW. -
Mod.TY]
